// https://www.shadertoy.com/view/ml3fDn triangle to kissing circles, 2023 by jt

// Given any triangle calculate radii so that circles placed at the vertices touch.
// Additionally the enclosing circle is displayed (if it exists).

// Related:
// https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_Apollonius
// https://www.shadertoy.com/view/Msc3Wn Problem of Apollonius
// https://rasmusfonseca.github.io/implementations/apollonius3d.pdf
// https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descartes%27_theorem
// https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soddy_circles_of_a_triangle
// https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SoddyCircles.html
// https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TangentSpheres.html

// Can this be extended to four spheres?
// Possible approach:
// * Calculate three kissing circles
// * Solve the Problem of Apollonius in 2d to obtain an enclosing circle
// * Add a third dimension (z=0, circles become spheres)
// * Solve the Problem of Apollonius in 3d to obtain a sphere touching the original three and the enclosing one
// Somewhat complicated. Perhaps there's a simpler solution...

// In the article "The Soddy spheres of a 4-ball tetrahedron"
// (by M. Fox, A. Oldknow, J. Rigby and C. Zeeman)
// an extension to a special class of tetrahedra is mentioned.

// tags: circles, triangle, tangent, apollonius, descartes, soddy, kissing

